Patch: aurora include/dolphin/ppc_math.h -- frsqrte's exponent-bias constant
       needs an unsigned shift, not a signed one.
Applies to: Aurora repo itself (external_refs/repos/aurora), commit 1dde08f.
Tracked file, edited directly (not a FetchContent dependency).
This is the second of two real, load-bearing Aurora-side bugs found while
diagnosing why a byte-correct sprite draw still produced a solid-black
window (the first was patch #3's unaligned load, in this same directory).

Why:
Once the game's own big-endian data was fixed to be byte-correct
and Aurora's own MTX/VEC library was linked in for the first time (a
separate finding, not part of this patch), the very first real light-
direction vector normalize (`Hu3DGLightCreate` -> `HuNormVecF` ->
`PSVECNormalize`) crashed the whole process:

    thread NNNN panic: left shift of 3068 by 52 places cannot be
    represented in type 'long long'
      include/dolphin/ppc_math.h:120 in frsqrte
      lib/dolphin/mtx/vec.c:57 in PSVECNormalize

Root cause: `frsqrte()`'s exponent-bias constant is declared with a
SIGNED 64-bit literal suffix:

    new_exp = ((uint64_t)((0xbfcLL << EXPONENT_SHIFT_F64) - exponent) >> 1)
               & EXPONENT_MASK_F64;

`0xbfc` is 3068 decimal; `EXPONENT_SHIFT_F64` is 52. `3068 << 52`
(~1.38e19) exceeds `INT64_MAX` (~9.22e18) -- the shift's mathematical
result cannot be represented in `int64_t` at all, which is undefined
behavior per the C standard REGARDLESS of the actual runtime value of
`exponent` (i.e. this fires for every single call, not just an edge
case -- confirmed: it crashed on `PSVECNormalize({0,0,1})`, about as
ordinary an input as exists). Plain clang/gcc (and, presumably, the
original MSVC build this header was written against) silently wrap this
to a two's-complement bit pattern and move on; zig cc's runtime UB
instrumentation traps it instead, the same category of "latent portability
landmine only zig's stricter runtime catches" as this directory's existing
patch #3 (`command_processor.cpp`'s unaligned load). Every OTHER 64-bit
mask/shift constant in this exact file (`MANTISSA_MASK_F64`,
`EXPONENT_MASK_F64`, `SIGN_MASK_F64`, every entry in `RSQRTE_TABLE`) is
already correctly `ULL`-suffixed -- this one constant is the sole,
clearly-accidental inconsistency.

Fix: change the one literal's suffix from `LL` (signed) to `ULL`
(unsigned). `uint64_t - int64_t` already promotes the signed operand to
unsigned per the usual arithmetic conversions (so the subtraction itself
was never the problem), and unsigned overflow is well-defined modular
wraparound in C -- producing the exact same bit pattern plain clang/gcc's
"silent" signed-overflow handling already gave in practice, just without
triggering the UB classification zig's runtime traps. The result is
masked with `& EXPONENT_MASK_F64` immediately afterward regardless, so
only the low bits ever mattered to begin with.

--- a/include/dolphin/ppc_math.h
+++ b/include/dolphin/ppc_math.h
@@ -117,7 +117,7 @@ static inline double frsqrte(double val) {
   }

   key = (uint32_t)(((uint64_t)exponent | mantissa) >> 37);
-  new_exp = ((uint64_t)((0xbfcLL << EXPONENT_SHIFT_F64) - exponent) >> 1) & EXPONENT_MASK_F64;
+  new_exp = ((uint64_t)((0xbfcULL << EXPONENT_SHIFT_F64) - exponent) >> 1) & EXPONENT_MASK_F64;

   entry = &RSQRTE_TABLE[0x1fu & (key >> 11)];
   result.u = new_exp | (uint64_t)(entry->base + entry->dec * (int64_t)(key & 0x7ffu));

Verified: after this change, PSVECNormalize/frsqrte no longer panics for
any input exercised during boot (light-direction normalize, camera-basis
normalize, sprite-group rotation axis normalize all confirmed working via
direct instrumentation), and produces numerically correct results
(spot-checked: frsqrte(1.0) round-trips to a rsqrt of 1.0 after Newton-
Raphson refinement, matching plain 1/sqrt(1.0)).

Rebuild after applying: `cmake --build aurora/build --target aurora_mtx`
(the only target whose sources include this header).
